Ownership means each value has one owner, and the value is dropped when that owner goes out of scope.

```rust
fn main() {
    let name = String::from("Ferris");
    greet(name);
}

fn greet(name: String) {
    println!("Hello, {name}");
}
```

The `String` moves into `greet`, so `greet` becomes responsible for it.

Borrowing lets code use a value without taking ownership of it.

```rust
fn print_len(text: &String) {
    println!("{}", text.len());
}

fn main() {
    let text = String::from("rust");
    print_len(&text);
    println!("{}", text);
}
```

The `&String` parameter borrows `text`, so `main` can still use it afterward.
